\begin_layout Subsection
Assumptions, dependencies and constraints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The client is using the app through a new generation smartphone
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The mobile device has a GPS system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The mobile device has a regular 3G internet connection available
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The software is designed to be utilized in Italy, precisely in the region
 of Lombardy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Public transits companies provide a sms-based purchasing system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The user has already logged in to his/her iCloud account (which is compulsory
 on all iOS and macOS devices) so that we can identify him/her by using
 the unique iCloud Keychain identifier
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Vehicle-sharing/ride-sharing companies' will provide APIs to locate the
 nearest vehicle available
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Weather forecast are provided from an external service through API
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
While calculating the shortest path, follows a time-based criteria instead
 of a cost-based one
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Interfaces to other applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the first stages of the project, Travlendar+ will not release API interfaces
 to the public
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Public transit pass
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system will not take into consideration whether the person owns a transit's
 pass, however it always allows to buy a transit ticket via text-message
 if asked by the user
\end_layout

